EQT's modeled fair value has been reset from $65.96 to $70.48, placing the stock closer to the upper end of recent analyst price target ranges. Many of these revisions are tied to different readings of commodity price assumptions, gas marketing execution, and how the market might value free cash flow and capital discipline. As you read on, you will see how to track these moving pieces and what they could mean for your own view on EQT.
Stay updated as the Fair Value for EQT shifts by adding it to your watchlist or portfolio. Alternatively, explore our Community to discover new perspectives on EQT.
Several firms, including JPMorgan and Mizuho, recently lifted EQT price targets into the low US$70s, reflecting updated models tied to commodity strip pricing and revised oil and gas assumptions.
Wells Fargo and TD Cowen highlight EQT's focus on commercial optimization, targeted curtailments, and infrastructure investments, linking these to free cash flow and capital efficiency in their raised targets.
Barclays, BMO Capital, Morgan Stanley, Jefferies and others have adjusted targets upward around recent earnings and sector updates, indicating interest in EQT's execution and exposure to oil and gas cash flow themes.
Truist's initiation with a positive stance reinforces the view from several banks that EQT's asset base, marketing approach, and cost profile support the current valuation framework.
TPH&Co. downgraded EQT, and firms such as UBS, Stephens and Bernstein have also trimmed targets in some updates, signaling caution around valuation sensitivity to changing commodity assumptions.
Roth Capital flags higher than expected derivative losses and maintains a Neutral view, and another Roth report cites expectations that gas prices could undershoot the 2026 futures curve, which could weigh on upside scenarios some other banks are using.
